olk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1400–Abt 1461":"circa 1400–circa 1461","1400–1461":"1400–1461","–Male":"Overleden","–1470":"–1470","1427–1498":"1427–1498","1460–1506":"1460–1506","1360–1444":"1360–1444","1380–1477":"1380–1477","Aft 1444":"na 1444","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","Abt 1400":"circa 1400","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","Abt 1426":"circa 1426","Abt 1461":"circa 1461","1477":"1477","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1498":"1498","1506":"1506","1427":"1427","Gissing, Norfolk, England":"Gissing, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kirby Cane, Norfolk, England":"Kirby Cane, Norfolk, England","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Pattishall, Northamptonshire, England":"Pattishall, Northamptonshire, England","Kirby, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1400–Abt 1461":"about 1400–about 1461","1400–1461":"1400–1461","–Male":"Deceased","–1470":"–1470","1427–1498":"1427–1498","1460–1506":"1460–1506","1360–1444":"1360–1444","1380–1477":"1380–1477","Aft 1444":"after 1444","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","Abt 1400":"about 1400","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","Abt 1426":"about 1426","Abt 1461":"about 1461","1477":"1477","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1498":"1498","1506":"1506","1427":"1427","Gissing, Norfolk, England":"Gissing, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Kirby Cane, Norfolk, England":"Kirby Cane, Norfolk, England","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Pattishall, Northamptonshire, England":"Pattishall, Northamptonshire, England","Kirby, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kemp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: status name for a champion, Middle English and Middle Low German <i>kempe</i>. In the Middle Ages a champion was a professional fighter on behalf of others; for example the King's Champion, at the coronation, had the duty of issuing a general challenge to battle to anyone who denied the king's right to the throne. The Middle English word corresponds to Old English <i>cempa</i> and Old Norse <i>kempa</i> ‘warrior’; both these go back to ancient Germanic <i>campo</i> ‘warrior’, which is the source of the Dutch and North German name, corresponding to High German   Kampf  .","Dutch and North German (North Rhine-Westphalia): from the personal name <i>Kempe</i>, <i>Kampe</i>; see 1 above.","Dutch and Flemish: metonymic occupational name for someone who grew or processed hemp, from Middle Dutch <i>canep</i> ‘hemp’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kampf","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (mainly <b>Kämpf</b>): from Middle High German <i>kampf</i>, German <i>Kamf</i> ‘fight, struggle’, hence an occupational name for a champion, a professional fighter (see   Kemp  ), or a nickname for someone with a pugnacious temperament. As a Jewish name it can be artificial. Compare   Kaempf  .","German: extended form of   Kamp   1."]},{"name":"Kemps","meanings":["Dutch and Flemish: genitivized form of   Kemp   2 or 4, concentrated in North Brabant and adjacent northern Belgium.","English (London): variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempt","meanings":["Scottish and English: perhaps from a shortened form of the extinct Scottish surname <i>Kemptie</i>, of uncertain origin, or an altered form of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Ilse.  Scandinavian Detlev, Gunhild.","English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempel","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempke","meanings":["North German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempker","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempkes","meanings":["North German and Dutch: genitivized pet form of   Kemp   2. Particularly in North Rhine-Westphalia and adjacent Gelderland."]},{"name":"Kempner","meanings":["German:","occupational name for a champion at jousting or wrestling, an agent derivative of <i>Kempe</i> ‘fight’ (see   Kemp  ).","habitational name, with agent suffix <i>-er</i>, for someone from any of various places called Kempen (notably near Krefeld) or from Kempno near Poznań, Poland."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Kemp was born about 1400, in Gissing, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Kemp, was 42 and her mother, Katherine Hawker, was 22. She married Robert de Varde Sr about 1426, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died about 1461, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 63, and was buried in Surrey, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1400–Abt 1461":"umbes 1400–umbes 1461","1400–1461":"1400–1461","–Male":"Surnud","–1470":"–1470","1427–1498":"1427–1498","1460–1506":"1460–1506","1360–1444":"1360–1444","1380–1477":"1380–1477","Aft 1444":"pärast 1444","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","13